			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Legalizing Recreational Drugs
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1849254">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Drugs are usually expensive.  Stoners are probably paying $300/month to keep their habit.  Depending on where they're at in the abuser spectrum and their economic situation, they're possibly cutting corners somewhere else or stealing it.<br />
<br />
Here's 2 facts about drugs that get overlooked a lot, along with my opinion based on them on why this is an important fact<br />
1) Most Drugs can be dangerous on their own, but when you buy them on the street, they're often far more dangerous.  Cocaine cut with borax and lidocaine, marijuana grown with non-safe pesticides, MDMA that's really meth[1].  Most of the anti-drug propaganda uses facts about these unsafe versions of the drug to propagate why they need to remain illegal.  Moving them from felony to civil crimes (the cops take your drugs and destroy them, and give you a fine, to avoid the fine a judge may require you to go into rehab) could also allow better testing facilities.  Selling pure MDMA? The fine is $500/unit.  Selling MDMA cut with a dangerous substance?  Felony.<br />
<br />
2) Many, possibly most, of the recreational drugs are used for a reason.  Maybe it isn't a good reason, but outside of painkiller addictions, people don't start consuming drugs habitually because they HAVE to.  Watching shows on NatGeo or whatever you see it all the time.  Guy wants to buy marijuana, dealer says &quot;sorry, all out, but try this, it's just as good.&quot;  Next thing you know the user is doing meth.  And a lot of the time drug problems can be cured with other illegal drugs.  Heroin users replace heroin with opioids that don't last as long in the system, which means when they finally go through withdrawal, it's a lot faster.  Multiple small sample studies have shown that people who have ruined their lives through addiction can turn their life around after a single hallucinogen 'trip'.  Scientists should be able to test that kind of effect.  Maybe they need to register with the government or something so the government can make sure everyone just out of college isn't slapping &quot;scientist&quot; on their job title in order to sell drugs, but it's irrelevant. The war on drugs removing the ability of scientists to do science has done no one any favors.  While it's been a known use case among users for a while, scientists finally got to study Ketamine as an antidepressant.  Huge surprise, it works great.  And unlike most of the antidepressants on the market, you take it once, and while it might fuck you up for a few hours, then you're fine for multiple weeks.  As opposed to my friends who have been prescribed prescription antidepressants and become vaguely suicidal robots.<br />
<br />
When those of us that are against the War on Drugs say we want drugs decriminalized, we're not saying we want Meth stores on the corner. We're saying sending someone to prison where we pay $60,000 per year for them to be there gains us nothing. And treating drugs as if our categorization of them is magical doesn't help society ever.<br />
<br />
[1] I actually hear that 'real' meth (like they kind they 'used to' give soldiers) is just mentally addictive, and less so than lots of legal substances we don't even think of as drugs.  But my case still stands, replacing something not addictive with something addictive (even if only barely) is fucked up.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
